?CO-TENANCY SHARED FACILITIES AGREEMENT This CO-TENANCY SHARED FACILITIES AGREEMENT (this “Agreement”) is made as of October 25, 2024 (“Execution Date”) by and between Clearwater Wind II, LLC, a Delaware limited liability company (“CWII” or “Shared Facilities Manager”), and Clearwater Wind III, LLC, a Delaware limited company (“CWIII” and together with CWII, the “Co-Tenants” or “Project Companies”). CWII and CWIII are referred to herein individually as a “Party” and collectively as the “Parties.” RECITALS WHEREAS, CWII owns and operates a wind-powered electrical generating facility with an expected nameplate capacity of approximately 103 megawatts located in Rosebud County, Montana (the “CWII Facility”); WHEREAS, CWIII is developing and constructing, and will own and operate, a wind-powered electrical generating facility with an expected nameplate capacity of approximately 100 megawatts located in Rosebud County, Montana, which is near the CWII Facility but does not include the Shared Facilities (the “CWIII Facility” and, together with the CWII Facility, the “Generating Facilities” and each, individually, a “Generating Facility”); WHEREAS, CWII has previously owned, operated and maintained the Shared Facilities (as defined below), and upon the effective date of, and pursuant to the terms of, the Co-Tenancy Agreement (as defined below), the Shared Facilities will be owned by the Co-Tenants;
WHEREAS, pursuant to the Land Agreement, the Co-Tenants have agreed to share certain easements and property rights that provide for the right to develop, construct, own, operate and/or maintain the Shared Facilities on the real property as more particularly described in such Land Agreement; and
WHEREAS, the Shared Facilities are essential for the interconnection and delivery of electric energy produced by each Generating Facility to the point of interconnection with the Colstrip Transmission System set forth in the LGIA and the Shared Interconnection Rights Agreement;
WHEREAS, in light of the essential nature of the Shared Facilities for operation of each Generating Facility, CWII and CWIII have entered into that certain Co-Tenancy Agreement dated as of October 25, 2024 (“Co-Tenancy Agreement”) under which CWII has conveyed an interest in the Shared Facilities to CWIII, such that CWII owns a 50.00% interest in the Shared Facilities and CWIII owns a 50.00% interest in the Shared Facilities, and which governs the terms and conditions of the ownership of the Shared Facilities located on the Real Property (as defined in the Land Agreement), as well as certain rights related to the use of such Shared Facilities by the Parties as tenants-in-common;
WHEREAS, the Parties intend that through the joint ownership arrangement of the Shared Facilities as set forth in the Co-Tenancy Agreement and this Agreement, each Party will own a sufficient interest in the Shared Facilities to provide for the production and delivery of energy from its Generating Facility to the point of interconnection with the Colstrip Transmission System set forth in the LGIA and the Shared Interconnection Rights Agreement and meet their respective obligations under the Power Purchase Agreements (as defined below).
NOW, THEREFORE, in consideration of the mutual premises set forth above and the covenants, agreements and provisions made in this Agreement, and for other good and valuable consideration, the receipt and sufficiency of which is hereby acknowledged, each of the Parties agrees as follows: AGREEMENT 1. DEFINITIONS; INTERPRETATION 1.1 Definitions . provided, however, that no Party shall be considered an Affiliate of any other Party for purposes of Article 7. “Agreement” has the meaning set forth in the preamble to this Agreement. “Applicable Law” means any duly promulgated Federal, state and local law, regulation, rule, ordinance, code, decree, judgment, directive or judicial or administrative order, permit and other duly authorized and valid action of any Governmental Authority applicable to any of the Shared Facilities, any Generating Facility, this Agreement or any Party, as applicable. “Bankruptcy Event” means, with respect to a Person, if such Person (a) voluntarily files a petition or otherwise commences, authorizes or acquiesces in the commencement of a proceeding or cause of action under any bankruptcy, insolvency, reorganization or similar law, (b) has any such petition filed or proceeding or action commenced against it by its creditors and such petition, proceeding or action is not dismissed within sixty (60) days after the filing or commencement, (c) except for an assignment pursuant to Section 11.2.2, makes an assignment or any general arrangement for the benefit of creditors, (d) has a liquidator, administrator, receiver, trustee, conservator or similar official appointed with respect to it or any substantial portion of its property or assets or (e) is generally unable to pay its debts as they fall due. “Budget” has the meaning set forth in Section 4.13.1. “Business Day” means any day, other than a Saturday, Sunday or any other day on which commercial banks in the State of Colorado or the State of New York are required or authorized to close. “Claims” means any and all claims, demands, suits, obligations, payments, liabilities, costs, fines, penalties, sanctions, taxes, judgments, damages, losses and expenses, including reasonable attorneys’ fees and expenses. “Clearwater Energy Resources” means Clearwater Energy Resources LLC, the counterparty to the LGIA with the Transmission Providers.
“Clearwater East” means Clearwater Wind East, LLC.

In this Agreement, unless a clearly contrary intention appears (a) the singular number includes the plural number and vice versa, (b) reference to any Person includes such Person’s successors and permitted assigns, (c) reference to any gender includes each other gender, (d) reference to any agreement (including this Agreement), document or instrument means such agreement, document or instrument as amended or modified and in effect from time to time in accordance with the terms thereof and, if applicable, hereof, (e) reference to any Article, Section or Exhibit means such Article, Section or Exhibit to this Agreement and references in any Article, Section, Exhibit or definition to any clause means such clause of such Article, Section, Exhibit or definition, (f) “hereunder,” “hereof,” “hereto,” “herein,” “herefrom,” and words of similar import are references to this Agreement as a whole and not to any particular Article, Section, Exhibit or other provision hereof, (g) relative to the determination of any period of time, “from” means “from and including,” “to” means “to but excluding” and “through” means “through and including,” (h) “including” (and with correlative meaning “include”) means including without limiting the generality of any description preceding such term, (i) reference to any Applicable Law means any such Applicable Law as amended, modified, codified or reenacted, in whole or in part, and in effect from time to time, and includes any rules and regulations promulgated thereunder and (j) unless otherwise agreed, all consents and notifications required under this Agreement shall be in writing (with an email exchanged between the appropriate Parties being a sufficient writing for these purposes). 2. TERM; TERMINATION 2.1 Term . The term of this Agreement shall commence on the Effective Date and shall terminate upon the first occurrence of one of the following (a) a single Co-Tenant becomes owner of the entire ownership interest in all of the Shared Facilities, (b) the mutual written agreement of all of the Co-Tenants, (c) the termination of the Co-Tenancy Agreement, or (d) as otherwise may be provided under this Agreement (the “Term”). Upon expiration of the Term, each of the Parties shall be released from all of its obligations under this Agreement, except for those obligations that survive the expiration of the Term pursuant to Section 11.4. 3. REGULATORY MATTERS AND EFFECTIVE DATE 3.1 Filing . The Parties shall file this Agreement with FERC pursuant to Section 205 of the Federal Power Act as soon as practicable after execution of the Agreement. 3.2 Cooperation . Each Party shall provide any information reasonably requested by any other Party in connection with any filing made pursuant to Section 3.1 and shall otherwise reasonably cooperate with, and act in good faith to assist, each other Party in acquiring any FERC action that such Party deems to be necessary or desirable with respect to this Agreement. 3.3 Effective Date. This Agreement shall become effective on the same date that the Co-Tenancy Agreement becomes effective, or on such other date as determined by FERC pursuant to the filing required under Section 3.1 (the “Effective Date”). 4. SHARED FACILITIES AND THE GENERATING FACILITIES 4.1 Shared Facilities. 4.1.1 Ownership. (a) Pursuant to this Agreement and the Co-Tenancy Agreement, the Co-Tenants shall own the Shared Facilities as tenants-in-common, with each Co-Tenant owning an undivided ownership interest in all Shared Facilities in proportion to its Co-Tenancy Percentage Interest (a “Co-Tenancy Interest”). (b) The Parties acknowledge and agree that the Shared Facilities Manager, and each Project Company, may be a party to one or more agreements associated with the Shared Facilities or the Shared Interconnection Rights Agreement. Without limiting the generality of Section 4.3, the Shared Facilities Manager shall comply with all the terms and conditions of this Agreement, the Land Agreement, the Shared Interconnection Rights Agreement and Governmental Approvals. 4.1.2 Waiver of Partition. The Co-Tenants recognize that the physical partition of the Shared Facilities or any part thereof, whether by partition in-kind or sale and division of the proceeds thereof, would be impossible and impractical and wholly inconsistent with the purposes for which this Agreement is made. ACCORDINGLY, EACH CO-TENANT HEREBY AGREES (FOR ITSELF AND FOR EACH OF ITS SUCCESSORS AND ASSIGNS) THAT IT SHALL NOT TAKE ANY ACTION AT ANY TIME, BY JUDICIAL PROCEEDING OR OTHERWISE, TO PARTITION THE SHARED FACILITIES OR ANY PART THEREOF, IN ANY WAY, WHETHER BY PARTITION IN KIND OR BY SALE AND DIVISION OF THE PROCEEDS THEREOF. FURTHER, EACH CO-TENANT IRREVOCABLY WAIVES THE RIGHT OF PARTITION AND THE BENEFIT OF ALL STATUTORY OR COMMON LAW THAT MAY NOW OR HEREAFTER AUTHORIZE SUCH PARTITION OF THE SHARED FACILITIES OR ANY PART THEREOF. Each Co-Tenant and its Lender (if any) shall be entitled to a decree or order restraining or enjoining such partition, application, action or proceeding upon any breach of the provisions of this Section 4.1.2. The Co-Tenants acknowledge and agree that they have been paid full consideration for the waiver herein provided. The Lender (if any) of each Co-Tenant is hereby made a third-party beneficiary of the waiver and covenants herein provided. The Co-Tenants agree that they will not participate in or permit any revocation, termination or amendment of such waiver or covenants without the prior written consent of the Lender (if any) of each Co-Tenant. 4.1.3 Use. (a) Each Project Company shall have an undivided right to the use or capacity of the applicable Shared Facilities up to (but not in excess of) its Co-Tenancy Percentage Interest therein and may use the Shared Facilities for the purpose of transmitting energy from, and receiving energy for its Generating Facility, as applicable, in accordance with the Power Purchase Agreements, the LGIA, the Shared Interconnection Rights Agreement and any agreements to provide back feed service or station power service for the Generating Facilities. Each Project Company shall only interconnect its Generating Facility (and no other facility) to the Shared Facilities. (b) In no event shall any Project Company’s use of the Shared Facilities or operation of its Generating Facility interfere with the use and quiet enjoyment by any Co-Tenant of such other Co-Tenant’s Co-Tenancy Interests in, or any Project Company’s rights to use, the Shared Facilities or any other Project Company’s operation of its Generating Facility, except as specifically provided herein or as agreed to by the Project Companies. Each of the Project Companies shall cooperate in good faith to accommodate the other Project Companies’ use of the Shared Facilities for the benefit of each other Project Company’s Generating Facility, as contemplated by this Agreement. The Project Companies acknowledge and agree that the use of the Shared Facilities by any Project Company in conformance with the terms of its Power Purchase Agreement and the Shared Interconnection Rights Agreement, in connection with its Generating Facility, as contemplated herein, will not, separately or in the aggregate, constitute an overburdening of the Shared Facilities or any part thereof. No Project Company shall use or permit the use of the Shared Facilities in any manner that would create unreasonable waste or nuisance, or that would jeopardize the issuance or maintenance of any insurance policy relating to the Shared Facilities or any Generating Facility, or any Governmental Approval for the Shared Facilities or any Generating Facility, or otherwise conduct or cause to be conducted operations with respect to the Shared Facilities or such Project Company’s Generating Facility that would have a similar effect on, or otherwise materially damage or interfere with, the Shared Facilities, unless otherwise agreed to by the Project Companies. (c) Either Party exercising its rights under this Section 4.1.3 shall, to the fullest extent commercially reasonable and subject to Prudent Industry Practice: (i) limit any interference with the use by the Parties of the Shared Facilities or their Generating Facilities; (ii) schedule during an off-peak and/or down-time period any required disconnection of the Shared Facilities (should such disconnection result in interference with the use by the non-exercising Party of the Shared Facilities) or another Party’s Generating Facility to conduct testing or operational activities in order to minimize the impact on the Generating Facilities; and (iii) provide prior written notice to the non-exercising Party of commencement of such activities together with a reasonably detailed description thereof, including dates and times of such disconnection, if any. In addition, the Party conducting such activities shall reimburse the other Party for all Net Lost Profits and any actual, out-of-pocket costs for such Co-Tenant’s Project arising out of any periods of disconnection resulting from the exercise of rights under this Section 4.1.3, it being hereby agreed that payment of the Net Lost Profits and costs shall be such Co-Tenant’s sole and exclusive remedy with respect to loss of revenue and other consequential damages arising out of the exercise of such rights. The Parties agree that the actual consequential damages arising out of such periods of disconnection would be difficult to compute and that the methodology for determining such damages set forth above is a good faith estimate of the calculations utilized to determine the actual consequential damages that would be suffered. 4.1.4 After-Acquired Property and Rights . All Additional Shared Facilities shall be directly acquired and held by the Co-Tenants as tenants-in-common, with each Co-Tenant owning its Co-Tenancy Interest therein. Unless otherwise determined by the Co-Tenants, any Co-Tenant, Affiliate of any Co-Tenant, member of any Co-Tenant, or Affiliate of any member of any Co-Tenant, that acquires in its own name, or an Affiliate’s name, any Additional Shared Facilities shall acquire and hold the same subject in all respects to this Agreement, and such Co-Tenant shall transfer and assign an undivided ownership interest therein to the other Co-Tenants equal to such other Co-Tenant’s Co-Tenancy Percentage Interest within thirty (30) days after such acquisition, and do all things necessary or appropriate to register or record on any appropriate register the asset in the names of the Co-Tenants. If such Additional Shared Facilities are encumbered by Liens (other than Excluded Liens) at the time of such conveyance, such Co-Tenant shall promptly and diligently work to remove such Liens from such Additional Shared Facilities. No Co-Tenant shall acquire an interest in any Additional Shared Facilities in violation of this Section 4.1 without the consent of the other Co-Tenant (not to be unreasonably withheld, delayed or conditioned). 4.2 Joint Responsibilities of the Project Companies . The Project Companies shall: (a) directly enter into or obtain all agreements associated with Shared Facilities; (b) provide the Shared Facilities Manager with such assistance as is reasonably required for the Shared Facilities Manager, acting as agent for the Co-Tenants as applicable, to acquire all Governmental Approvals that are necessary for the ownership, operation and maintenance of the Shared Facilities; (c) operate their respective Generating Facilities in accordance with the LGIA, the Shared Interconnection Rights Agreement, this Agreement and their respective Power Purchase Agreements, including the scheduling requirements under this Agreement, the LGIA, Shared Interconnection Rights Agreement and Power Purchase Agreements, unless the failure to do so does not adversely affect the development, construction, ownership, operation or maintenance of the Shared Facilities; (d) use the Shared Facilities in accordance with all Applicable Laws, Governmental Approvals and the Shared Interconnection Rights Agreement with respect to their respective Generating Facilities; and (e) obtain and maintain all Governmental Approvals required in connection with their respective use of the Shared Facilities. 4.3 Shared Facilities Manager. 4.3.1 General Responsibilities . The Project Companies hereby appoint the Shared Facilities Manager to act as their agent with respect to the overall pursuit and management of all aspects of the Shared Facilities, including day-to-day management and decision-making. The Shared Facilities Manager shall have the power to exercise any and all of the rights of the Shared Facilities Manager, as set forth herein, and the obligation to perform the services required herein of the Shared Facilities Manager. Without limiting the generality of the foregoing sentence, the Shared Facilities Manager shall: (a) pursue and manage the timely operation and maintenance of all Shared Facilities in accordance with all (i) Applicable Laws, (ii) all Governmental Approvals, (iii) Prudent Industry Practices, (iv) the Shared Facilities O&M Agreement, (v) any warranties applicable to the Shared Facilities, (vi) the Power Purchase Agreements, and (vii) the Shared Interconnection Rights Agreement (including the scheduling requirements under this Agreement and the LGIA), while at all times limiting any interference with the use of the Shared Facilities, the Easement Property or the applicable Generating Facility by any Co-Tenant (collectively, the “Requirements”); (b) act as agent for the Project Companies in acquiring all Governmental Approvals that are necessary for the ownership, operation and maintenance of the Shared Facilities; (c) act as agent for the Project Companies under the Shared Interconnection Rights Agreement and undertake all activities as the designated Shared Facilities Manager thereunder, including coordinating notices relating to the Shared Facilities, receiving operating instructions and ensuring responsive actions, receiving invoices and other communications from Clearwater Energy Resources, and performing all other tasks and actions contemplated under the Shared Interconnection Rights Agreement to be performed by the Shared Facilities Manager; (d) pursue and manage, including through the Shared Facilities O&M Agreement, the operation and maintenance of the Shared Facilities in a reliable manner, in good working order and on a non-discriminatory basis, and, to the extent it does not cause a breach or violation of any Applicable Law, Governmental Approval, Prudent Industry Practice, the Shared Interconnection Rights Agreement, or any Power Purchase Agreement, in a manner so to maximize each Generating Facility’s revenue, which operation and maintenance shall include the performance of repairs in an expeditious manner that minimizes each Generating Facility’s downtime and otherwise reduces overall repair costs and damages; (e) coordinate the administrative obligations of the Project Companies under this Agreement and the Shared Interconnection Rights Agreement, including billing, payments and communications; (f) procuring and maintaining the insurance required to be maintained with respect to the Parties for the Shared Facilities as set forth on Schedule I of the Co-Tenancy Agreement; (g) pursue and manage the repair or replacement of Shared Facilities affected by any Event of Loss or Condemnation Action. 4.3.2 Non-Delegable Actions . Notwithstanding anything in Section 4.3.1 to the contrary, the following actions by the Shared Facilities Manager shall require the consent of the Co-Tenants (in each case not to be unreasonably withheld, delayed or conditioned): (a) the submission of any initial application for any non-ministerial Governmental Approval for the Shared Facilities, the application for renewal or material modification of any such Governmental Approval or the acceptance of any such Governmental Approval or material modification thereto; (b) the selection of any major contractor or vendor with respect to the Shared Facilities; (c) commit to expenditures in excess of the amounts set forth in any Budget, for or on behalf of the Co-Tenants, except in the case of Emergencies; (d) the execution, termination of, amendment to, issuance of a material change order under, or waiver of a provision of this Agreement or any Other Agreements; (e) the adoption of, and modifications to, any Budget; (f) the initiation of any litigation, arbitration or other dispute resolution mechanism relating to the Shared Facilities or otherwise or the settlement of any of the foregoing or any insurance or warranty claim relating to the Shared Facilities; (g) the disposition of any Shared Facilities (other than dispositions in the ordinary course of business of surplus or obsolete assets having a value of less than One Hundred Thousand U.S. Dollars ($100,000) or in connection with a transfer of all of a Co-Tenant’s rights in its Generating Facility); (h) the acquisition of insurance for the Shared Facilities except as set forth on Schedule I of the Co-Tenancy Agreement, and any modifications thereto; (i) to borrow funds or otherwise incur indebtedness on behalf of any Co-Tenant; (j) creating, or causing to be created, any Lien on any of the Shared Facilities, the Easement Property or any Generating Facility; and (k) the determination to commence the wind-up of the Shared Facilities. 4.3.3 Subcontracting . The Shared Facilities Manager shall not subcontract any of its rights, duties, or responsibilities under this Agreement without the prior written consent of each Co-Tenant; provided, however, that the prior written consent of the Co-Tenants will be deemed to have been provided for the Shared Facilities O&M Agreement or if such subcontracting arrangement is set forth in a Budget that is approved in accordance with Section 4.13. 4.3.4 Replacement . Upon the written approval of all Project Companies, the Project Companies may replace the Shared Facilities Manager with any Person of their choosing. 4.3.5 Fees and Expenses . The Project Companies shall reimburse the Shared Facilities Manager in accordance with the Sharing Ratio for all reasonable out-of-pocket expenses incurred by the Shared Facilities Manager pursuant to this Agreement in accordance with Section 6.2. 4.3.6 Performance; Non-Discrimination . The Shared Facilities Manager shall exercise its rights and perform its obligations hereunder in accordance with the Requirements. The Shared Facilities Manager shall keep proper books, records and other documents with respect to the Shared Facilities and make such books, records and other documents reasonably available to the Project Companies for inspection or audit. 4.4.2 Access . Each Project Company shall (a) review and comment on draft revisions to this Agreement and any Governmental Approvals for the Shared Facilities and (b) be provided copies by each other Project Company and/or the Shared Facilities Manager of all Governmental Approvals for the Shared Facilities (including applications therefor), material communications regarding the Shared Facilities and all information related to land rights, operation, maintenance or use costs, creditworthiness, records, operating data, accounts, copies of studies, reports and data and any other information regarding the Shared Facilities, in each case, as reasonably requested by such Project Company. 4.5 Notification and Emergencies. (a) Each Project Company shall promptly notify the other Parties of any known Emergency (and any action taken pursuant thereto), Force Majeure or default under this Agreement and the Shared Interconnection Rights Agreement, violation under any Applicable Law or Governmental Approval related to the Shared Facilities, other material event, planned maintenance or repair on the Shared Facilities or any other situation or condition that could reasonably be expected to prompt an interruption, reduction or curtailment of, or have a material adverse effect on, the Shared Facilities, the Generating Facilities or the Shared Interconnection Rights Agreement. (b) Notwithstanding anything in this Agreement to the contrary, during an Emergency, any Party may take any action reasonably prudent or necessary to (i) preserve public health and safety, (ii) limit or prevent damage to the Shared Facilities, the Generating Facilities or other property or persons and (iii) discharge its duties or obligations under the Shared Interconnection Rights Agreement; provided that such actions are made in good faith and are consistent with Prudent Industry Practice or in accordance with the Shared Interconnection Rights Agreement and such Party uses reasonable efforts to minimize the adverse effect of such actions on the Shared Facilities, the Shared Interconnection Rights Agreement and the Generating Facilities. 4.6 Modifications . Upon the request of any of the Parties (the “Requesting Party”), the Shared Facilities Manager shall timely undertake and complete any upgrades, modifications and expansions of the Shared Facilities that result in Additional Shared Facilities (a “Modification”); provided that (a) no Modification shall be undertaken without the consent of the non-Requesting Parties (not to be unreasonably withheld, delayed or conditioned) and (b) no Modification shall cause a breach or violation of any Applicable Law, Governmental Approval, Prudent Industry Practice, this Agreement, any Power Purchase Agreement, or the Shared Interconnection Rights Agreement. At the direction of the Shared Facilities Manager acting in accordance with its rights and responsibilities under this Agreement, the Project Companies shall promptly curtail deliveries of energy to or on the Shared Facilities (a) when necessary in order maintain or repair any part of the Shared Facilities being performed in accordance with the terms of this Agreement, (b) if necessary for safety or Emergencies or if the energy delivered to, or transmitting on, the Shared Facilities does not conform to this Agreement or jeopardizes the integrity or use of the Shared Facilities, (c) if required pursuant to, or to comply with, the Shared Interconnection Rights Agreement, (d) if Shared Facilities Manager or any Project Company is otherwise required to do so in accordance with any applicable requirements of the organization certified by FERC to propose and enforce mandatory standards for the reliable operation and planning of the bulk power system throughout the United States of America, (e) if the Project Companies’ rights under the Shared Interconnection Rights Agreement are curtailed, and (f) as otherwise agreed to by the Project Companies. In the event of any curtailment of the deliveries of energy to or on the Shared Facilities at the direction of the Transmission Providers, the Project Companies shall limit the length of such curtailment to that time reasonably necessary to address the event or circumstance resulting in such interruption, reduction or curtailment or otherwise to comply with the Shared Interconnection Rights Agreement. 4.7.2 Allocation. In the event of any curtailment of interconnection services at the direction of Transmission Providers, such curtailment shall be allocated pro rata among (a) CWII and (b) CWIII; provided, however, that the Shared Facilities Manager shall only curtail CWII and CWIII on a non-pro rata basis if it determines in accordance with Prudent Industry Practices that non-pro rata allocation of such curtailment is necessary to comply with the Shared Interconnection Rights Agreement or is at the Transmission Provider’s direction, and, in each case, that such non-pro rata allocation will not result in a default under the Shared Interconnection Rights Agreement. 4.7.3 Excess Usage . If any Project Company is using the Shared Facilities in excess of its rights under this Agreement, then such Project Company shall cause such excess usage to be reduced, interrupted and curtailed. 4.8.4 Breach of the Shared Interconnection Rights Agreement. If a Co-Tenant is in breach of the Shared Interconnection Rights Agreement that requires the curtailment of the other Co-Tenant’s Generating Facility, the Shared Facilities Manager is authorized to curtail or disconnect such Generating Facility until such alleged breach is cured if doing so (x) results in a cure of an alleged breach and (y) following consultation and agreement with Clearwater Energy Resources that the Transmission Providers will allow the non-breaching Generating Facility to continue or resume delivering the output from such Generating Facility to the Point of Interconnection. 4.8 Liens . No Co-Tenant shall create or permit to exist any Lien (other than an Excluded Lien) on its Co-Tenancy Interests without the consent of the other Co-Tenants. No Co-Tenant shall create or cause to exist any Lien on the other Co-Tenant’s Generating Facility or Co-Tenancy Interests; provided, however, that any Co-Tenant may obtain a judgment Lien against the other Co-Tenant based on such other Co-Tenant’s breach under this Agreement or otherwise permitted at law or in equity not specifically prevented by this Agreement. If any such Lien not permitted pursuant to this Section 4.9 attaches, or a Co-Tenant receives notice of any such Lien, the Party whose actual or alleged act or omission resulted in such Lien shall cause such Lien to be released and removed of record within fifteen (15) days of such attachment or notice, unless such Party: (a) in good faith contests or disputes the claim or claims of the lienholders and the validity of such Liens; (b) promptly commences legal action to remove such Lien and posts any bond required under Applicable Law; and (c) furnishes to the other Co-Tenant and its Lenders a bond or other security acceptable to the other Co-Tenant and Lenders, acting in their reasonable discretion, in an amount sufficient to discharge all such contested Liens during such period the lienholders’ proceedings are stayed. 4.9 Non-Disturbance . Such Party breaches a representation or warranty it has made hereunder in any material respect and such breach is not remedied within thirty (30) days after notice thereof is provided to such Party; 9.1.4 Non-Disturbance . Any breach of Section 4.1.3(b) or 4.10 or any non-disturbance agreement executed by the Parties pursuant to Section 4.10 and such breach is not cured within (a) the time period specified for cure in any such non-disturbance agreement, and (b) for a breach of Section 4.1.3(b) or 4.10, or if a time period for cure is not specified in such non-disturbance agreement, within two (2) Business Days following written notice from the Shared Facilities Manager or any other Co-Tenant specifying the nature of such breach; 9.1.5 Liens . With respect to any Co-Tenant, such Co-Tenant breaches its obligations under Section 4.9 and such breach is not remedied within fifteen (15) days after notice thereof is provided to such Co-Tenant; and 9.1.6 Bankruptcy . The occurrence of a Bankruptcy Event with respect to such Party. Notwithstanding anything in this Section 9.1 to the contrary, if a breach of this Agreement by a Party would cause a Party to cause a breach of the Shared Interconnection Rights Agreement, any notice or cure period provided in this Section 9.1 shall be equal to the lesser of (a) the notice or cure period provided in this Section 9.1 for such breach and (b) the notice or cure period provided in the Shared Interconnection Rights Agreement. 9.2 Remedies. 9.2.1 Cumulative Remedies . If an Event of Default occurs, each Non-Defaulting Party shall be entitled to all legal and equitable remedies at law or in equity not expressly prohibited by the terms of this Agreement; except that this Agreement may only be terminated as provided in Section 2.1. 9.2.2 Specific Performance . Each Party acknowledges and agrees that the failure to perform any of its obligations under this Agreement would cause irreparable harm to the other Parties and that the remedy at law for any violation or threatened violation thereof would be inadequate, and further agrees that the other Parties shall be entitled to a temporary or permanent injunction, specific performance or other equitable relief specifically to enforce such obligations without the necessity of proving the inadequacy of its legal remedies. No Party shall be required to post any guaranty, letter of credit, bond or other security to obtain an order or decree of temporary or permanent injunction, specific performance or other equitable relief. 9.2.3 Loss of Right to Shared Facilities . If an Event of Default occurs under Section 9.1, then, without limiting any other rights that any Non-Defaulting Party might otherwise have, upon notice to the Defaulting Party delivered while such Event of Default remains outstanding, (a) any Non-Defaulting Party may curtail such Defaulting Party’s benefit or use of, or access to, the Shared Facilities and (b) if a Project Company is a Non-Defaulting Party, such Project Company may receive all or any part of the Defaulting Party’s rights under this Agreement to benefit, use and access the Shared Facilities (or, if not practicable due to regulatory requirements or the rights of third Persons, the Defaulting Party shall promptly pay over to such Project Company all proceeds from its benefit, use and access of the Shared Facilities) until such time as such default has been cured, including, if applicable, each Non-Defaulting Party’s receipt of an amount equal to any payment default plus interest at the Interest Rate. 9.2.4 Cure Rights . If an Event of Default has occurred that could reasonably be expected to have a material adverse effect on the Shared Facilities or under Section 9.1.5, then, without limiting any other rights that the Non-Defaulting Party might have, upon notice to the Defaulting Party delivered while such Event of Default remains outstanding, each Non-Defaulting Party may cure such Event of Default at the Defaulting Party’s expense; provided, however, that no Party shall have the right to make any modification to any Generating Facility that is not owned by such Party. 10. LENDER PROTECTIONS 10.1 Applicability Generally. The following provisions are for the benefit of the Lenders (if any) of each Party, and provided that notice of the identity and contact information of such Lender has been given to the other Parties in accordance with Section 11.3 of this Agreement, shall apply to a Party while there exists any outstanding amount payable, or any performance required, by such Party to such Party’s Lender. Once a Party has indefeasibly paid all of the outstanding amounts payable to, and rendered all performance required by such Party to its Lender, then such Party shall provide prompt notice to the other Parties thereof and, solely with respect to that Party, all references in this Agreement to the Lender shall be deemed null and void and all such provisions shall, without any further actions, have no further force and effect; provided, however, that such provisions shall be revived if such Party assigns its interest in this Agreement as collateral security to a Lender in connection with a further financing transaction and gives notice of the identity and contact information of such Lender to the other Parties in accordance with Section 11.3. 10.2 Cure Rights. The following provisions are for the benefit of the Lenders (if any) of each Party, and provided upon the occurrence of an Event of Default by a Party, or if such Party should dissolve or be subject to a voluntary or involuntary Bankruptcy Event, such Party’s Lender shall have the right, but not the obligation to (a) make any payments due under this Agreement by such Party; and (b) do any other act or thing on behalf of such Party that may be necessary or appropriate to be done in the performance and observance of the terms hereof. All payments so made, and all things so done and performed, by a Lender on behalf of such Party shall be as effective to prevent or cure any breach or Event of Default as they would have been if made, done and performed by such Party, and each Party agrees to accept such performance, payment and cure by such Lender acting in place of such Party. Each Party agrees to make all payments (if any) to be made by it to a Defaulting Party directly to such Defaulting Party’s Lender upon receipt of the Lender’s written instructions to that effect. 10.3 Amendment. Each Party agrees for the benefit of a Lender (if any) of the other Party that it will not, without the prior written consent of such Lender (which consent shall be given or withheld on the basis of the documents governing the relationship between such Lender and such other Party) amend, modify or waive or take any action causing, consenting to or accepting the amendment, modification or waiver of any provision of this Agreement. 10.4 Default Notices. Each Party shall deliver to a Lender (if any) of the Defaulting Party a duplicate copy of any and all notices of Default that it may from time to time deliver to a Defaulting Party hereunder, and such copies shall be delivered to such Lender at the same time such notices of Default are delivered to such Defaulting Party. No such notice of Default shall be deemed to have been given to a Defaulting Party hereunder unless and until a copy thereof shall have been given to the Defaulting Party’s Lenders. 10.5 Failure to Cure. Upon a Defaulting Party’s failure to cure any Event of Default hereunder within the time provided in Section 9.1 hereof (including any extended cure periods which may be applicable thereunder), then the Lender (if any) of such Defaulting Party shall have an additional sixty (60) days after expiration of such cure period to cure such Event of Default; provided, however, that if such Event of Default cannot reasonably be cured within such additional sixty (60) day period, then such Lender shall have such additional time to cure such Event of Default as may be reasonably necessary; provided, further, that such cure period shall in no event, unless otherwise provided herein, be extended beyond one hundred eighty (180) days. Any Event of Default that cannot be cured by such Lender shall nevertheless be deemed to have been cured and remedied if (a) on or before sixty (60) days after receiving such notice of Default, such Lender (or its designee) shall have acquired (i) control of the Defaulting Party, or (ii) the Defaulting Party’s then-remaining right, title and interest in and to this Agreement, the Co-Tenancy Interest, and any individually owned Defaulting Party assets located on the Easement Property and used in connection with the Defaulting Party’s Project (collectively, the “Project Assets”), or shall have commenced foreclosure or other appropriate proceedings for such purposes and shall be prosecuting such proceedings to completion with commercially reasonable diligence, and (b) promptly upon obtaining control of the Defaulting Party or the Defaulting Party’s then-remaining Project Assets, subject to Section 10.9 hereof, the Defaulting Party’s Lender (or its designee) assumes in writing, and commences performance of, the obligations of the Defaulting Party hereunder. All rights of the Parties to terminate this Agreement as a result of the occurrence of an Event of Default hereunder shall be expressly conditioned upon (i) the Defaulting Party’s Lender having first received a copy of the notice of Default as and when provided in Section 10.4 hereof and (ii) the Lender having failed to cure the Event of Default or acquire possession of the Defaulting Party or the Defaulting Party’s Project Assets or commence foreclosure or other appropriate proceedings as set forth, and within the time specified, in this Section 10.5. 10.6 Extension of Time to Cure. If a Lender is prohibited by any process or injunction issued by, or by reason of any action of, any court having jurisdiction over any bankruptcy, reorganization, insolvency or other debtor-relief proceeding from commencing or prosecuting foreclosure or other appropriate proceedings, then the times specified in Section 10.5 hereof for commencing or prosecuting such foreclosure or other proceedings shall be extended for the period of such prohibition. 10.7 Consent to Transfer. The transfer of (i) control of a Defaulting Party, or (ii) a Defaulting Party’s Project Assets or any part thereof, to the Defaulting Party’s Lender and/or to one or more purchasers or grantees (a) at a foreclosure sale by judicial or nonjudicial foreclosure and sale, (b) by a conveyance in lieu of foreclosure or (c) by any other assignment or conveyance, including by such Lender or such other purchaser(s) or grantee(s) following foreclosure and sale, or as a result of any other legal proceeding, shall not require the consent of the other Parties, and such other Parties agree that upon such foreclosure, sale, conveyance, assignment or other proceeding, it shall recognize the Lender or such other purchaser(s) or grantee(s) as the successor to the Defaulting Party under this Agreement; provided, however, that, subject to Section 10.9 hereof, the Lender or such purchaser(s) or grantee(s) assumes the obligations of the Defaulting Party under this Agreement. 10.8 New Agreement. In the event that this Agreement is terminated without Lender’s written consent for any reason other than an Event of Default which could have been but was not cured by the Lender as provided in this Article 10, and if, within sixty (60) days after receiving notice of such termination, the Lender shall so request, then, so long as the Lender is making commercially reasonable efforts to cure any Event of Default by the Defaulting Party as provided herein, the other Parties shall execute and deliver to the Lender or its designee one or more new agreements, which new agreement(s) shall be on the same terms and conditions as this Agreement for the remaining Term of this Agreement before giving effect to such termination. 10.9 Liability of Lender. A Defaulting Party’s Lender or any such purchaser(s) or grantee(s) described in Section 10.7 hereof shall not have any duty, obligation or liability under this Agreement prior to the time of its entry into physical possession of the Project Assets or its commencement of performance of a Defaulting Party’s obligations under this Agreement or under a new agreement entered into as provided in Section 10.8 hereof, and shall not otherwise be required to perform (or be subject to any defenses or offsets by reason of) any Defaulting Party’s other obligations under this Agreement that were unperformed at such time. In the event that the Defaulting Party’s Lender elects to perform a Defaulting Party’s obligations under this Agreement or to enter into a new agreement as provided in Section 10.8 hereof, then the Lender shall not have any personal liability to any Party for the performance of such obligations, and the sole recourse of such Parties in seeking the enforcement of such obligations shall be to the Lender’s interest in the Defaulting Party’s Project Assets. In the event that the Lender assigns its interest in this Agreement or a new agreement entered into pursuant to Section 10.8 hereof to any purchaser(s) or grantee(s) described in Section 10.7 hereof, then the Lender shall be released from any further liability hereunder, provided that such purchaser(s) or grantee(s) assume the obligations of the Defaulting Party under this Agreement arising after the Lender’s entry into physical possession or the Lender’s commencement of performance of the Defaulting Party’s obligations. 10.10 Cooperation. A Party shall, upon not less than ten (10) days prior written notice from any other Party or such other Party’s Lender, execute an estoppel certificate (a) certifying that this Agreement is in full force and effect and has not been modified except as specified in this Agreement or as set forth in such certificate, (b) certifying that, to such Party’s knowledge, there are no uncured Events of Default under this Agreement (or, if any such uncured Events of Default exist, stating with particularity the nature thereof), and (c) containing any other certifications as may reasonably be requested by a Lender and agreed to by such Party. In addition, a Party shall, upon not less than thirty (30) days prior written notice from any Lender to another Party or from another Party, and at such other Party’s expense, execute and deliver such other documents as may be reasonably requested by such Lender or Party, including consents to assignment, legal opinions and similar agreements or instruments. 10.11 Assumption in Writing. Subject to Section 10.9 of this Agreement, each Party agrees to have its successor under this Agreement assume in writing its obligations under this Agreement; provided, however, that nothing contained herein shall be deemed a consent by any Lender to any assignment that is prohibited, or to which any Lender may withhold its consent under any applicable financing documents. 11. GENERAL 11.1 Disputes. 11.1.1 Notice; Referral . In the event any Party has a dispute, or asserts a Claim, that arises out of or in connection with this Agreement, such Party (the “Disputing Party”) shall provide the other Parties with written notice of the dispute or Claim (“Notice of Dispute”). Such dispute or Claim shall be referred to a designated senior representative of each Party for resolution on an informal basis as promptly as practicable after receipt of the Notice of Dispute by the Parties. In the event the designated representatives are unable to resolve the Claim or dispute through unassisted or assisted negotiations within thirty (30) days of the other Parties’ receipt of the Notice of Dispute, each Party may exercise whatever rights and remedies it may have in equity or at law consistent with the terms of this Agreement. 11.1.2 Federal Power Act . Except as provided in Section 11.17, nothing in this Agreement shall abrogate or otherwise limit a Party’s right to exercise any rights it may have under the Federal Power Act; provided, however, that, except in an Emergency, a Party shall not exercise its rights under the Federal Power Act until thirty (30) days after receipt of the applicable Notice of Dispute. 11.1.3 Attorney’s Fees and Costs. If any Party institutes any legal action or other proceeding for the enforcement, termination, cancellation, or rescission hereof, or for damages for the breach hereof, the prevailing Party in such action or proceeding shall be entitled to recover its reasonable attorney's fees and all its court and other costs (including in any appellate proceeding or any bankruptcy proceeding). 11.2 Assignment Restrictions. 11.2.1 Assignment . Except as provided in Section 11.2.2 or 11.2.4, no Party shall assign its rights or obligations under this Agreement and no Co-Tenant shall assign its Co-Tenancy Interests; provided, however, that such Party shall assign (such assignment not requiring consent of a Party) all of its rights under this Agreement and all of its Co-Tenancy Interests to a transferee of all or substantially all of such Party’s rights in its Generating Facility (in which case such transferee shall be assigned and assume the transferring Party’s entire interest in both this Agreement and Co-Tenancy Interests (if any), pursuant to an agreement reasonably satisfactory to the other Parties). 11.2.2 Financing; Right to Encumber . Notwithstanding anything in this Section 11.2 to the contrary and in addition to the rights and obligations of any Party set forth in any consent to assignment but subject to Section 4.10, each Project Company shall have the right to assign to its Lenders any of its rights and obligations under this Agreement and any of its Co-Tenancy Interests (if any), in each case, without consent, only for collateral security purposes to aid in providing financing for such Project Company’s Generating Facility and Co-Tenancy Interest (if any) in the Shared Facilities. At the requesting Project Company’s cost, the other Project Company and the Shared Facilities Manager each agrees to execute and deliver to and in favor of the Lenders a consent to assignment and such other documents customary for such financing transactions and reasonably requested by such Lenders and reasonably acceptable to the Parties. 11.2.3 Void . Any assignment in contravention of this Section 11.2 shall be null and void. 11.2.4 Subcontracts . Notwithstanding anything in this Section 11.2 to the contrary, but subject to the provisions of Section 4.3.3, a Party may enter into subcontracts to perform its obligations under this Agreement, but such Party shall not be relieved of any obligation hereunder. 11.2.5 Benefit of Lenders. The provisions of this Section 11.2 and any other provision of this Agreement that requires the consent or approval of any Lender for any purpose are for the benefit of each Lender as well as the Parties hereto and shall be enforceable by each Lender as an express third-party beneficiary hereof. Each Party hereby agrees that no Lender shall be obligated to perform any obligation or be deemed to incur any liability or obligation provided in this Agreement on the part of another Party or shall have any obligation or liability to another Party with respect to this Agreement except to the extent such Lender has expressly assumed the obligations hereunder pursuant to Section 10.9 or pursuant to any agreement with any such Lender entered into hereafter pursuant to Section 10.8. 11.3 Notices . Any notice, demand, or communication required or permitted to be given by any provision of this Agreement shall be deemed to have been sufficiently given or served for all purposes if delivered personally or by telecopy to the Party or, if sent by registered or certified mail, postage and charges prepaid, addressed to the Party’s address, as appropriate, which is set forth below or to such other address as a Party shall advise the other Parties from time to time in writing. 11.4 Survival . The following shall survive expiration of the Term: (a) all obligations under this Agreement owed to a Party arising prior to or resulting from the expiration of, or on account of the breach of, this Agreement; (b) Sections 4.3 and 7.1, which shall survive to the full extent of the statute of limitations period applicable to any Claim, (c) the resolution of any dispute or Claim submitted pursuant to this Agreement prior to, or resulting from, the expiration of the Term; and (d) Articles 1, 9 and 11 and Sections 6.1.3, 7.2 and 7.3. 11.5 Waivers . No (a) failure or delay on the part of a Party in exercising any of its rights under this Agreement or in insisting upon strict performance of provisions of this Agreement, (b) partial exercise by a Party of any of its rights under this Agreement or (c) course of dealing among the Parties, shall constitute a waiver of the rights of any Party under this Agreement. Any waiver of rights shall be effective only by a written instrument signed by the Party granting any such waiver, and such instrument shall not operate as a waiver of, or estoppel with respect to, any subsequent failure to comply herewith. 11.6 Consents. Wherever the consent or approval of any Party is required under this Agreement, such consent or approval shall not be unreasonably withheld, unless this Agreement expressly provides that such consent or approval is to be given by such Party at the sole or absolute discretion of such Party or is otherwise similarly qualified. 11.7 No Partnership . This Agreement shall not be interpreted or construed to create an association, joint venture, agency relationship or partnership between the Parties or to impose any partnership obligation or partnership liability upon any Party. Except as otherwise agreed to by the Parties or expressly provided herein, no Party shall have any right, power or authority to enter into any agreement or undertaking for, or act on behalf of, or to act as or be an agent or representative of, or to otherwise bind, the other Party. No Project Company nor any Affiliate of a Project Company shall be precluded from engaging in any activities, including activities similar or identical to those to be conducted by the other Project Company, in respect of its Generating Facility, the Shared Facilities or the Shared Interconnection Rights Agreement or any activities incidental or related thereto, in each case, except as provided in this Agreement or as agreed to by the Project Companies. 11.8 Headings . The captions of the Articles and Sections of this Agreement are solely for convenience and shall not be deemed a part of this Agreement for the purpose of construing the meaning of this Agreement or for any other purpose. 11.9 Governing Law . This Agreement and the rights of the Parties hereunder shall be construed in accordance with the laws of the State of Colorado to the extent not governed by the Federal Power Act, and all rights and remedies shall be governed by such laws without regard to principles of conflict of laws that require the application of another jurisdiction’s laws. 11.10 Severability . The invalidity or enforceability of any particular provision of this Agreement shall not affect the other provisions hereof, and this Agreement shall be construed in all respects as if such invalid or unenforceable provisions were omitted, and in lieu of such invalid or unenforceable provision, there shall be added automatically as a part of this Agreement a valid and enforceable provision as similar in terms to such invalid or unenforceable provision as may be possible. 11.11 Entire Agreement . This Agreement, the Land Agreement, the Shared Facilities O&M Agreement and the Co-Tenancy Agreement contain all agreements of the Parties with respect to the subject matter hereof, and all other prior or contemporaneous agreements, understandings, correspondence and negotiations among the Parties, whether oral or written, pertaining to the subject matter of this Agreement, shall be of no further force or effect, and are superseded hereby. This Agreement shall not be construed in any manner to amend or otherwise modify the Shared Interconnection Rights Agreement. 11.12 Counterparts . This Agreement may be executed in any number of counterparts with the same effect as if all the Parties had signed the same document. All counterparts shall be construed together and shall constitute one instrument. 11.13 Successors and Assigns . This Agreement shall be binding upon and inure to the benefit of all the Parties and their respective successors and permitted assigns. 11.14 Third-Party Beneficiaries . The covenants contained herein are made solely for the benefit of the Parties and their respective successors and assigns as permitted herein, and shall not be construed as having been intended to benefit any Person who is not a Party other than as expressly provided with respect to each Lender in Articles 10 and 11. By the acceptance of any of the benefits of any of the provisions of this Agreement, each Lender shall be deemed to have agreed to comply with any obligation expressly imposed upon a Lender pursuant to this Agreement. 11.15 Joint Preparation . This Agreement shall be considered for all purposes as having been prepared through the joint efforts of the Parties and shall not be construed against any Party as a result of the preparation, substitution, submission or other event of the negotiation, drafting or execution of this Agreement. 11.16 Amendment . This Agreement may be amended, supplemented or modified only by a written instrument duly executed by or on behalf of each Party. 11.17 Mobile Sierra . The Parties agree that all rates, terms and conditions as specified in this Agreement shall remain in effect in accordance with their terms and shall not be subject to change through application to FERC pursuant to the provisions of Section 205 or Section 206 of the Federal Power Act of 1935, as amended, 16 U.S.C. §§ 792 et seq. Absent agreement of the Parties to a proposed change, the standard of review for changes to any section of this Agreement by a Party, a non-Party or FERC acting sue sponte, shall be the “public interest” standard of review set forth in United Gas Pipe Line Co. v. Mobile Gas Service Corp., 350 U.S. 332 (1956) and Federal Power Commission v. Sierra Pacific Power Co., 350 U.S. 348 (1956), or will be the most stringent standard permissible under then-Applicable Law. 11.18 Confidentiality . Each Party agrees to maintain the confidentiality of information clearly identified at the time of delivery as confidential provided by a Party pursuant to this Agreement, except that such information may be disclosed (a) to Affiliates, managers, members, directors, officers, employees, advisors, agents, consultants, Lenders and potential lenders, investors and purchasers to or of a Party or any of its Affiliates (and their respective advisors, consultants and counsel); it being understood that the Persons to whom such disclosure is made will be informed of the confidential nature of such information, (b) to the extent required by any Governmental Authority having jurisdiction over the receiving Party or Applicable Law (provided that to the extent such confidential information may be excluded from any such report, statement or testimony, or may be submitted subject to administrative confidentiality protection, in each case without prejudicing in any manner the position of the receiving Party, such receiving Party shall exclude the information or submit it subject to confidentiality protection), (c) in any legal action or proceeding relating to this Agreement or any Generating Facility, or (d) to the extent such information (i) becomes publicly available other than by breach of this Section 11.18, (ii) was available to the receiving Party on a non-confidential basis prior to its disclosure by the disclosing Party, (iii) becomes available to the receiving Party on a non-confidential basis from a third-Person not under any obligation to the disclosing Party not to disclose such information or (iv) is independently developed by the receiving Party. 11.19 Further Assurances . Each Party shall take all such further actions, and execute and deliver all such further instruments or documents, as may be reasonably requested by any other Party to effectuate the purposes of this Agreement. 11.20 Time is of the Essence. Time is of the essence with respect to the obligations to be performed under this Agreement, such that deadlines for performance of obligations shall be strictly observed for purposes of determinations of compliance and damages; provide, however, that materiality with respect to obligations and compliance therewith shall be judged independently of this Section 11.20 in connection with any determination of whether an Event of Default has occurred.
